# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: quasar-framework
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Within computing, **cross-platform software** (also called **multi-platform software**, **platform-agnostic software**, or **platform-independent software**) is computer software that is designed to work in several computing platforms.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] For example, a cross-platform application may run on Linux, macOS and Microsoft Windows.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform software may run on many platforms, or as few as two.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Some frameworks for cross-platform development are Codename One, ArkUI-X, Kivy, Qt, GTK, Flutter, NativeScript, Xamarin, Apache Cordova, Ionic, and React Native.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] A hardware platform can refer to an instruction set architecture.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] For example: ARM or the x86 architecture.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] These machines can run different operating systems.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Smartphones and tablets generally run ARM architecture, these often run Android or iOS and other mobile operating systems.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] A software platform can be either an operating system (OS) or programming environment, though more commonly it is a combination of both.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] An exception is Java, which uses an OS-independent virtual machine (VM) to execute Java bytecode.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] The Java language is typically compiled to run on a VM that is part of the Java platform.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] The Java virtual machine (Java VM, JVM) is a CPU implemented in software, which runs all Java code.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] This enables the same code to run on all systems that implement a JVM.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Java software can be executed by a hardware-based Java processor.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] This is used mostly in embedded systems.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Java code running in the JVM has access to OS-related services, like disk input/output (I/O) and network access, if the appropriate privileges are granted.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] The JVM makes the system calls on behalf of the Java application.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] This lets users to decide the appropriate protection level, depending on an access-control list (ACL).
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] For example, disk and network access is usually enabled for desktop applications, but not for browser-based applets.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] The Java Native Interface (JNI) can also be used to access OS-specific functions, with a loss of portability.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Currently, Java Standard Edition software can run on Microsoft Windows, macOS, several Unix-like OSs, and several real-time operating systems for embedded devices.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] For mobile applications, browser plugins are used for Windows and Mac based devices, and Android has built-in support for Java.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] There are also subsets of Java, such as Java Card or Java Platform, Micro Edition, designed for resource-constrained devices.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] For software to be considered cross-platform, it must function on more than one computer architecture or OS.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Developing such software can be a time-consuming task because different OSs have different application programming interfaces (API).
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Software written for one OS may not automatically work on all architectures that OS supports.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Just because software is written in a popular programming language such as C or C++, it does not mean it will run on all OSs that support that language—or even on different versions of the same OS.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Web applications are typically described as cross-platform because, ideally, they are accessible from any web browser: the browser is the platform.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Web applications generally employ a client–server model, but vary widely in complexity and functionality.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] It can be hard to reconcile the desire for features with the need for compatibility.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Basic web applications perform all or most processing from a stateless server, and pass the result to the client web browser.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] All user interaction with the application consists of simple exchanges of data requests and server responses.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] This type of application was the norm in the early phases of World Wide Web application development.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Such applications follow a simple transaction model, identical to that of serving static web pages.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Today, they are still relatively common, especially where cross-platform compatibility and simplicity are deemed more critical than advanced functionality.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Prominent examples of advanced web applications include the Web interface to Gmail and Google Maps.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Such applications routinely depend on additional features found only in the more recent versions of popular web browsers.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] These features include Ajax, JavaScript, Dynamic HTML, SVG, and other components of rich web applications.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Because of the competing interests of compatibility and functionality, numerous design strategies have emerged.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Many software systems use a layered architecture where platform-dependent code is restricted to the upper- and lowermost layers.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Graceful degradation attempts to provide the same or similar functionality to all users and platforms, while diminishing that functionality to a least common denominator for more limited client browsers.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] For example, a user attempting to use a limited-feature browser to access Gmail may notice that Gmail switches to basic mode, with reduced functionality but still of use.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Some software is maintained in distinct codebases for different (hardware and OS) platforms, with equivalent functionality.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] This requires more effort to maintain the code, but can be worthwhile where the amount of platform-specific code is high.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] This strategy relies on having one codebase that may be compiled to multiple platform-specific formats.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] One technique is conditional compilation.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] With this technique, code that is common to all platforms is not repeated.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Blocks of code that are only relevant to certain platforms are made conditional, so that they are only interpreted or compiled when needed.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Another technique is separation of functionality, which disables functionality not supported by browsers or OSs, while still delivering a complete application to the user.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] (See also: Separation of concerns.) This technique is used in web development where interpreted code (as in scripting languages) can query the platform it is running on to execute different blocks conditionally.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Third-party libraries attempt to simplify cross-platform capability by hiding the complexities of client differentiation behind a single, unified API, at the expense of vendor lock-in.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Responsive web design (RWD) is a Web design approach aimed at crafting the visual layout of sites to provide an optimal viewing experience—easy reading and navigation with a minimum of resizing, panning, and scrolling—across a wide range of devices, from mobile phones to desktop computer monitors.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Little or no platform-specific code is used with this technique.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform applications need much more integration testing.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Some web browsers prohibit installation of different versions on the same machine.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] There are several approaches used to target multiple platforms, but all of them result in software that requires substantial manual effort for testing and maintenance.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Techniques such as full virtualization are sometimes used as a workaround for this problem.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Tools such as the Page Object Model allow cross-platform tests to be scripted so that one test case covers multiple versions of an app.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] If different versions have similar user interfaces, all can be tested with one test case.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Web applications are becoming increasingly popular but many computer users still use traditional application software which does not rely on a client/web-server architecture.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] The distinction between traditional and web applications is not always clear.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Features, installation methods and architectures for web and traditional applications overlap and blur the distinction.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Nevertheless, this simplifying distinction is a common and useful generalization.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Traditional application software has been distributed as binary files, especially executable files.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Executables only support the platform they were built for—which means that a single cross-platform executable could be very bloated with code that never executes on a particular platform.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Instead, generally there is a selection of executables, each built for one platform.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] For software that is distributed as a binary executable, such as that written in C or C++, there must be a software build for each platform, using a toolset that translates—transcompiles—a single codebase into multiple binary executables.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] For example, Firefox, an open-source web browser, is available on Windows, macOS (both PowerPC and x86 through what Apple Inc. calls a Universal binary), Linux, and BSD on multiple computer architectures.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] The four platforms (in this case, Windows, macOS, Linux, and BSD) are separate executable distributions, although they come largely from the same source code.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] In rare cases, executable code built for several platforms is combined into a single executable file called a fat binary.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] The use of different toolsets may not be enough to build a working executables for different platforms.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] In this case, programmers must *port* the source code to the new platform.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] For example, an application such as Firefox, which already runs on Windows on the x86 family, can be modified and re-built to run on Linux on the x86 (and potentially other architectures) as well.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] The multiple versions of the code may be stored as separate codebases, or merged into one codebase.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] An alternative to porting is *cross-platform virtualization*, where applications compiled for one platform can run on another without modification of the source code or binaries.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] As an example, Apple's Rosetta, which is built into Intel-based Macintosh computers, runs applications compiled for the previous generation of Macs that used PowerPC CPUs.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Another example is IBM PowerVM Lx86, which allows Linux/x86 applications to run unmodified on the Linux/Power OS.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] A script can be considered to be cross-platform if its interpreter is available on multiple platforms and the script only uses the facilities built into the language.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] For example, a script written in Python for a Unix-like system will likely run with little or no modification on Windows, because Python also runs on Windows; indeed there are many implementations (e.g.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] The same goes for many of the open-source scripting languages.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Unlike binary executable files, the same script can be used on all computers that have software to interpret the script.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] This is because the script is generally stored in plain text in a text file.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] There may be some trivial issues, such as the representation of a new line character.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform or multi-platform is a term that can also apply to video games released on a range of video game consoles.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Examples of cross-platform games include: *Miner 2049er*, *Tomb Raider: Legend*, *FIFA series*, *NHL series* and *Minecraft*.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Each has been released across a variety of gaming platforms, such as the Wii, PlayStation 3, Xbox 360, personal computers, and mobile devices.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Some platforms are harder to write for than others, requiring more time to develop the video game to the same standard.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] To offset this, a video game may be released on a few platforms first, then later on others.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Typically, this happens when a new gaming system is released, because video game developers need to acquaint themselves with its hardware and software.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Some games may not be cross-platform because of licensing agreements between developers and video game console manufacturers that limit development to one particular console.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] As an example, Disney could create a game with the intention of release on the latest Nintendo and Sony game consoles.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Should Disney license the game with Sony first, it may be required to release the game solely on Sony's console for a short time or indefinitely.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Several developers have implemented ways to play games online while using different platforms.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Psyonix, Epic Games, Microsoft, and Valve all possess technology that allows Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3 gamers to play with PC gamers, leaving the decision of which platform to use to consumers.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] The first game to allow this level of interactivity between PC and console games (Dreamcast with specially produced keyboard and mouse) was *Quake 3*.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Games that feature cross-platform online play include *Rocket League*, *Final Fantasy XIV*, *Street Fighter V*, *Killer Instinct*, *Paragon* and *Fable Fortune,* and *Minecraft* with its Better Together update on Windows 10, VR editions, Pocket Edition and Xbox One.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform programming is the practice of deliberately writing software to work on more than one platform.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] There are different ways to write a cross-platform application.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] One approach is to create multiple versions of the same software in different *source trees*—in other words, the Microsoft Windows version of an application might have one set of source code files and the Macintosh version another, while a FOSS *nix system might have a third.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] While this is straightforward, compared to developing for only one platform it can cost much more to pay a larger team or release products more slowly.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] It can also result in more bugs to be tracked and fixed.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Another approach is to use software that hides the differences between the platforms.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] This abstraction layer insulates the application from the platform.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Such applications are *platform agnostic*.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Applications that run on the JVM are built this way.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Some applications mix various methods of cross-platform programming to create the final application.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] An example is the Firefox web browser, which uses abstraction to build some of the lower-level components, with separate source subtrees for implementing platform-specific features (like the GUI), and the implementation of more than one scripting language to ease software portability.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Firefox implements XUL, CSS and JavaScript for extending the browser, in addition to classic Netscape-style browser plugins.
[src:quasar-framework/cross-platform-software] Much of the browser itself is written in XUL, CSS, and JavaScript.
[src:quasar-framework/material-design] The purpose of developing Material Design was to create a novel visual language, synthesizing the classic principles of good design with the innovation and potential of technology and science.
[src:quasar-framework/material-design] Head designer Matías Duarte explained that "unlike real paper, our digital material expands and reforms intelligently.
[src:quasar-framework/material-design] Material has physical surfaces and edges.
[src:quasar-framework/material-design] Seams and shadows provide meaning about what you can touch." Material Design is based on paper-and-ink and skeuomorphic interaction concepts, but its implementation is more advanced.
[src:quasar-framework/material-design] In 2021, Google revamped the design language, with the new language being titled Material You (Material Design 3).
[src:quasar-framework/material-design] It provides more flexibility for designers to create custom themes with varying geometry, colors, and typography.
[src:quasar-framework/material-design] In 2025, the next evolution of the design language, titled "Material 3 Expressive", was unveiled.
[src:quasar-framework/material-design] Material Design has been gradually rolled out across Google's web and mobile products, providing a consistent experience across all platforms and applications.
[src:quasar-framework/material-design] Google has also released application programming interfaces (APIs) for third-party developers to incorporate the design language into their applications.
[src:quasar-framework/material-design] The canonical open source implementation of Material Design for web application user interfaces is called Material Web.
[src:quasar-framework/material-design] However, there are other official ways to do so, such as, for example, using Flutter or Jetpack Compose.
[src:quasar-framework/material-design] After the 2018 revamp, Google began redesigning most of their apps based on an updated set of principles and guidelines dubbed "Material Design 2", which appeared on Android Pie.
[src:quasar-framework/material-design] It provided a larger focus on customization of the basic Material Design components to adapt to the branding of the products in which it is being used.
[src:quasar-framework/material-design] The updated guidelines further heavily emphasize white space, rounded corners, colorful icons, and bottom navigation bars.
[src:quasar-framework/material-design] Google began utilizing a special size-optimized version of their proprietary Product Sans font called Google Sans.
[src:quasar-framework/material-design] At Google I/O in May 2021, Google announced a new concept on Android 12 known as "Material You" (also known as "Material Design 3"), emphasizing increased animation, larger buttons, and the ability for custom UI themes to be generated from the user's wallpaper.
[src:quasar-framework/material-design] Material You was gradually rolled out to various Google apps on older Android versions in the following months, and acted as a major focus on the Pixel 6 and Pixel 6 Pro smartphone series.
[src:quasar-framework/material-design] At The Android Show: I/O Edition in May 2025, Google announced "Material 3 Expressive" for Android 16 and Wear OS 6.
[src:quasar-framework/material-design] This version of Material Design shares similarities with its predecessor, and includes improved animations and a more colorful and fun design.
[src:quasar-framework/material-design] It was gradually rolled out to Pixel phones (Pixel 6 and newer) and the Pixel Tablet, beginning in September 2025.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] A **progressive web application** (**PWA**), or **progressive web app**, is a type of web app that can be installed on a device as a standalone application.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] PWAs are installed using the offline cache of the device's web browser.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] PWAs were introduced from 2016 as an alternative to native (device-specific) applications, with the advantage that they do not require separate bundling or distribution for different platforms.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] They can be used on a range of different systems, including desktop and mobile devices.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] Publishing the app to digital distribution systems, such as the Apple App Store, Google Play, or the Microsoft Store on Windows, is optional.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] Because a PWA is delivered in the form of a webpage or website built using common web technologies including HTML, CSS, JavaScript, and WebAssembly, it can work on any platform with a PWA-compatible browser.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] As of 2025, PWA features are supported to varying degrees by Google Chrome, Apple Safari, Brave, Firefox for Android, Microsoft Edge, and Firefox for Windows.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] At Apple's Worldwide Developers Conference in 2007, Steve Jobs announced that the iPhone would "run applications created with Web 2.0 Internet standards".
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] No software development kit (SDK) was required, and the apps would be fully integrated into the device through the Safari browser engine.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] This model was later switched to the App Store, as a means of appeasing frustrated developers.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] In October 2007 Jobs announced that an SDK would be launched the following year.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] As a result, although Apple continued to support web apps, the vast majority of iOS applications shifted toward the App Store.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] Beginning in the early 2010s dynamic web pages allowed web technologies to be used to create interactive web applications.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] Responsive web design, and the screen-size flexibility it provides have made PWA development more accessible.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] Continued enhancements to HTML, CSS, and JavaScript allowed web applications to incorporate greater levels of interactivity, making native-like experiences possible on a website.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] It was intended to be an open-source operating system for running web apps as native apps on mobile devices.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] Firefox OS was based on the Gecko rendering engine with a user interface called Gaia, written in HTML5.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] The development of Firefox OS ended in 2016, and the project was completely discontinued in 2017, although a fork of Firefox OS was used as the basis of KaiOS, a feature phone platform.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] Google then put significant efforts into promoting PWA development for Android.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] Firefox introduced support for service workers in 2016, and Microsoft Edge and Apple Safari followed in 2018, making service workers available on all major systems.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] By 2019, PWAs were supported by desktop versions of some browsers, including Microsoft Edge (on Windows) and Google Chrome (on Windows, macOS, ChromeOS, and Linux).
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] In December 2020, Firefox for desktop abandoned the implementation of PWAs (specifically, removed the prototype "site-specific browser" configuration that had been available as an experimental feature).
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] A Firefox architect noted: "The signal I hope we are sending is that PWA support is not coming to desktop Firefox anytime soon." Mozilla supports PWAs on Android and plans to keep supporting it.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] Firefox version 143.0, released in September 2025, added support for PWA on Windows.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] Progressive web apps are all designed to work on any browser that is compliant with the appropriate web standards.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] As with other cross-platform solutions, the goal is to help developers build cross-platform apps more easily than they would with native apps.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] Progressive web apps employ the progressive enhancement web development strategy.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] Some progressive web apps use an architectural approach called the App Shell Model.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] In this model, service workers store the Basic User Interface or "shell" of the responsive web design web application in the browser's offline cache.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] This model allows for PWAs to maintain native-like use with or without web connectivity.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] This can improve loading time, by providing an *initial static frame*, a layout or architecture into which content can be loaded progressively as well as dynamically.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] There are many technologies commonly used to create progressive web apps.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] A web application is considered a PWA if it satisfies the installation criteria, thus can work offline and can be added to the device's home screen.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] To meet this definition, all PWAs require at minimum a manifest and a service worker.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] Other technologies may be used to store data, communicate with servers or execute code.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] This metadata is crucial for an app to be added to a home screen or otherwise listed alongside native apps.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] iOS Safari partially implements manifests, while most of the PWA metadata can be defined via Apple-specific extensions to the meta tags.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] These tags allow developers to enable full-screen display, define icons and splash screens, and specify a name for the application.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] A service worker is a web worker that implements a programmable network proxy that can respond to web/HTTP requests from the main document.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] It is able to check the availability of a remote server, cache content when that server is available, and serve that content to the document later.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] Service workers, like any other web workers, work separately from the main document context.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] Service workers can handle push notifications and synchronize data in the background, cache or retrieve resource requests, intercept network requests and receive centralized updates independently of the document that registered them, even when that document is not loaded.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] Service workers go through a three-step lifecycle of Registration, Installation and Activation.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] Registration involves telling the browser the location of the service worker in preparation for installation.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] Installation occurs when there is no service worker installed in the browser for the web app, or if there is an update to the service worker.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] Activation occurs when all of the PWA's pages are closed, so that there is no conflict between the previous version and the updated one.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] The lifecycle also helps maintain consistency when switching among versions of a service worker since only a single service worker can be active for a domain.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] WebAssembly allows precompiled code to run in a web browser, at near-native speed.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] Thus, libraries written in languages such as C can be added to web apps.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] Announced in 2015 and first released in March 2017, WebAssembly became a W3C recommendation on December 5, 2019 and it received the Programming Languages Software Award from ACM SIGPLAN in 2021.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] is a WHATWG standard API that enables key–value storage in modern browsers.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] (that enables storage that persists across sessions).
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] is a W3C standard database API available in all major browsers.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] objects and any structures representable as a string.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] providing additional constructs around it.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] In 2017, Twitter released Twitter Lite, a PWA alternative to the official native Android and iOS apps.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] According to Twitter, Twitter Lite consumed only 1–3% of the size of the native apps.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] Starbucks provides a PWA that is 99.84% smaller than its equivalent iOS app.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] After deploying its PWA, Starbucks doubled the number of online orders, with desktop users ordering at about the same rate as mobile app users.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] A 2018 review published by Forbes, found that users of Pinterest's PWA spent 40% more time on the site compared to the previous mobile website.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] Ad revenue rates also increased by 44%, and core engagements by 60%.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] Flipkart saw 60% of customers who had uninstalled their native app return to use the Flipkart PWA.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] Lancôme saw an 84% decrease in time until the page is interactive, leading to a 17% increase in conversions and a 53% increase in mobile sessions on iOS with their PWA.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] Since a PWA does not require separate bundling or distribution for different platforms and is available to users via the web, it is not necessary for developers to release it over digital distribution systems like the Apple App Store, Google Play, Microsoft Store, or Samsung Galaxy Store.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] The major app stores support the publication of PWAs to varying degrees.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] Google Play, Microsoft Store, and Samsung Galaxy Store support PWAs, but Apple App Store does not.
[src:quasar-framework/progressive-web-app] Microsoft Store publishes some qualifying PWAs automatically (even without app authors' requests) after discovering them via Bing indexing.
[src:quasar-framework/quasar-framework] Quasar focuses on building VueJS user interfaces quickly.
[src:quasar-framework/quasar-framework] Quasar is designed with performance, responsiveness and inter-operability in mind.
[src:quasar-framework/quasar-framework] Quasar was created by Razvan Stoenescu after working for IBM and Lenovo using constantly new and different software tools to create all the separate types of iOS apps, Android apps, web applications, Windows Desktop apps, Apple Desktop apps, and PWAs.
[src:quasar-framework/quasar-framework] He later summed up his thought process: "I longed for a single framework that would remove all the complexity and produce all these different flavors of apps … from a SINGLE codebase.
[src:quasar-framework/quasar-framework] The first source code commit to the project was dated 2015, and Quasar stable 1.0 release was released in July 2019.
[src:quasar-framework/quasar-framework] The first Quasar conference took place in July 2020.
[src:quasar-framework/quasar-framework] Quasar v2 (with Vue.js 3) went stable in 2.0.0 release in June 2021.
[src:quasar-framework/quasar-framework] Quasar apps are built using Vue Single File Components and Quasar Components.
[src:quasar-framework/quasar-framework] Vue Single file components contain multiple sections: template (HTML), script (Javascript) and style (CSS/Stylus/SASS/SCSS/Less) - all in the same file.
[src:quasar-framework/quasar-framework] Quasar components are HTML tags that begin with `q` and link to the `/quasar.config` file.
[src:quasar-framework/quasar-framework] The core library comes with tools and libraries both developed by the core team and contributors.
[src:quasar-framework/quasar-framework] A command-line interface tool that facilitates the creation and development of cross-platform applications.
[src:quasar-framework/quasar-framework] It provides a global environment for app initialization and management.
[src:quasar-framework/quasar-framework] The local development and build environment within the Quasar CLI.
[src:quasar-framework/quasar-framework] A comprehensive library of user interface components designed for use within Quasar applications.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] A **single-page application** (**SPA**) is a web application or website that interacts with the user by dynamically rewriting the current web page with new data from the web server, instead of the default method of loading entire new pages.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] The goal is faster transitions that make the website feel more like a native app.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] In a SPA, a page refresh never occurs; instead, all necessary HTML, JavaScript, and CSS code is either retrieved by the browser with a single page load, or the appropriate resources are dynamically loaded and added to the page as necessary, usually in response to user actions.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] The origins of the term *single-page application* are unclear, though the concept was discussed at least as early as 2003 by technology evangelists from Netscape.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Earlier forms were called rich web applications.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] JavaScript can be used in a web browser to display the user interface (UI), run application logic, and communicate with a web server.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Mature free libraries are available that support the building of a SPA, reducing the amount of JavaScript code developers have to write.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] There are various techniques available that enable the browser to retain a single page even when the application requires server communication.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] HTML authors can leverage element IDs to show or hide different sections of the HTML document.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Then, using CSS, authors can use the `:target` pseudo-class selector to only show the section of the page which the browser navigated to.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Web browser JavaScript frameworks and libraries, such as Angular, Ember.js, ExtJS, Knockout.js, Meteor.js, React, Vue.js, and Svelte have adopted SPA principles.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Aside from ExtJS, all of these are free.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] JavaScript-based web application frameworks, such as React and Vue, provide extensive capabilities but come with associated trade-offs.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] These frameworks often extend or enhance features available through native web technologies, such as routing, component-based development, and state management.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Frameworks can introduce abstraction layers that may contribute to performance overhead, larger bundle sizes, and increased complexity.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Modern frameworks, such as React 18 and Vue 3, address these challenges with features like concurrent rendering, tree-shaking, and selective hydration.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] While these advancements improve rendering efficiency and resource management, their benefits depend on the specific application and implementation context.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Lightweight frameworks, such as Svelte and Preact, take different architectural approaches, with Svelte eliminating the virtual DOM entirely in favor of compiling components to efficient JavaScript code, and Preact offering a minimal, compatible alternative to React.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Framework choice depends on an application’s requirements, including the team’s expertise, performance goals, and development priorities.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] A newer category of web frameworks, including enhance.dev, Astro, and Fresh, leverages native web standards while minimizing abstractions and development tooling.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] These solutions emphasize progressive enhancement, server-side rendering, and optimizing performance.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Astro renders static HTML by default while hydrating only interactive parts.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Fresh focuses on server-side rendering with zero runtime overhead.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Enhance.dev prioritizes progressive enhancement patterns using Web Components.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] While these tools reduce reliance on client-side JavaScript by shifting logic to build-time or server-side execution, they still use JavaScript where necessary for interactivity.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] This approach makes them particularly suitable for performance-critical and content-focused applications.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] The following frameworks utilize WebAssembly or can build single-page applications (SPAs) with WebAssembly as a core technology or support mechanism.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] These frameworks enable high-performance and interactive client-side development, extending the SPA paradigm across languages and ecosystems.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] As of 2006, the most prominent technique used was Ajax.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Ajax involves using asynchronous requests to a server for XML or JSON data, such as with JavaScript's XMLHttpRequest or more modern `fetch()` (since 2017), or the deprecated ActiveX Object.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] In contrast to the declarative approach of most SPA frameworks, with Ajax the website directly uses JavaScript or a JavaScript library such as jQuery to manipulate the DOM and edit HTML elements.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Ajax has further been popularized by libraries like jQuery, which provides a simpler syntax and normalizes Ajax behavior across different browsers which historically had varying behavior.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] WebSockets are a bidirectional real-time client-server communication technology that are part of the HTML specification.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] For real-time communication, their use is superior to Ajax in terms of performance and simplicity.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Server-sent events (SSEs) is a technique whereby servers can initiate data transmission to browser clients.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Once an initial connection has been established, an event stream remains open until closed by the client.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] SSEs are sent over traditional HTTP and have a variety of features that WebSockets lack by design such as automatic reconnection, event IDs, and the ability to send arbitrary events.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Although this method is outdated, asynchronous calls to the server may also be achieved using browser plug-in technologies such as Silverlight, Flash, or Java applets.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Requests to the server typically result in either raw data (e.g., XML or JSON), or new HTML being returned.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] In the case where HTML is returned by the server, JavaScript on the client updates a partial area of the DOM (Document Object Model).
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] When raw data is returned, JavaScript on the client translates it into HTML using XSL or a JSON template before updating the DOM.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] A SPA moves logic from the server to the client, with the role of the web server evolving into a pure data API or web service.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] This architectural shift has, in some circles, been coined "Thin Server Architecture" to highlight that complexity has been moved from the server to the client, with the argument that this ultimately reduces overall complexity of the system.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] The server keeps the necessary state in memory of the client state of the page.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] In this way, when any request hits the server (usually user actions), the server sends the appropriate HTML and/or JavaScript with the concrete changes to bring the client to the new desired state (usually adding/deleting/updating a part of the client DOM).
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] At the same time, the state in server is updated.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Most of the logic is executed on the server, and HTML is usually also rendered on the server.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] In some ways, the server simulates a web browser, receiving events and performing delta changes in server state which are automatically propagated to client.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] This is a variant of the stateful server approach.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] The client page sends data representing its current state to the server, usually through Ajax requests.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] This approach requires that more data be sent to the server and may require more computational resources per request to partially or fully reconstruct the client page state in the server.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] At the same time, this approach is more easily scalable because there is no per-client page data kept in the server and, therefore, Ajax requests can be dispatched to different server nodes with no need for session data sharing or server affinity.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Some SPAs may be executed from a local file using the file URI scheme.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] This gives users the ability to download the SPA from a server and run the file from a local storage device, without depending on server connectivity.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] If such a SPA wants to store and update data, it must use browser-based Web Storage.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] These applications benefit from advances available with HTML.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Because the SPA is an evolution away from the stateless page-redraw model that browsers were originally designed for, some new challenges have emerged.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Because of the lack of JavaScript execution on crawlers of some popular Web search engines, SEO (search engine optimization) has historically presented a problem for public facing websites wishing to adopt the SPA model.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Between 2009 and 2015, Google Webmaster Central proposed and then recommended an "AJAX crawling scheme" using an initial exclamation mark in fragment identifiers for stateful AJAX pages (`#!`).
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Special behavior must be implemented by the SPA site to allow extraction of relevant metadata by the search engine's crawler.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] For search engines that do not support this URL hash scheme, the hashed URLs of the SPA remain invisible.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] These "hash-bang" URIs have been considered problematic by a number of writers including Jeni Tennison at the W3C because they make pages inaccessible to those who do not have JavaScript activated in their browser.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] They also break HTTP referer headers as browsers are not allowed to send the fragment identifier in the Referer header.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] In 2015, Google deprecated their hash-bang AJAX crawling proposal.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Alternatively, applications may render the first page load on the server and subsequent page updates on the client.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] This is traditionally difficult, because the rendering code might need to be written in a different language or framework on the server and in the client.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Using logic-less templates, cross-compiling from one language to another, or using the same language on the server and the client may help to increase the amount of code that can be shared.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] In 2018, Google introduced dynamic rendering as another option for sites wishing to offer crawlers a non-JavaScript heavy version of a page for indexing purposes.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Dynamic rendering switches between a version of a page that is rendered client-side and a pre-rendered version for specific user agents.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] This approach involves your web server detecting crawlers (via the user agent) and routing them to a renderer, from which they are then served a simpler version of HTML content.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] As of 2024, Google no longer recommends dynamic rendering, suggesting "server-side rendering, static rendering, or hydration" instead.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Because SEO compatibility is not trivial in SPAs, SPAs are commonly not used in a context where search engine indexing is either a requirement, or desirable.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Use cases include applications that surface private data hidden behind an authentication system.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] In the cases where these applications are consumer products, often a classic "page redraw" model is used for the applications landing page and marketing site, which provides enough meta data for the application to appear as a hit in a search engine query.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Blogs, support forums, and other traditional page redraw artifacts often sit around the SPA that can seed search engines with relevant terms.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] As of 2021 and Google specifically, SEO compatibility for a plain SPA is straightforward and requires just a few simple conditions to be met.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] One way to increase the amount of code that can be shared between servers and clients is to use a logic-less template language like Mustache or Handlebars.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Such templates can be rendered from different host languages, such as Ruby on the server and JavaScript in the client.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] However, merely sharing templates typically requires duplication of business logic used to choose the correct templates and populate them with data.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Rendering from templates may have negative performance effects when only updating a small portion of the page—such as the value of a text input within a large template.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Replacing an entire template might also disturb a user's selection or cursor position, where updating only the changed value might not.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] To avoid these problems, applications can use UI data bindings or granular DOM manipulation to only update the appropriate parts of the page instead of re-rendering entire templates.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] With a SPA being, by definition, "a single page", the model breaks the browser's design for page history navigation using the "forward" or "back" buttons.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] This presents a usability impediment when a user presses the back button, expecting the previous screen state within the SPA, but instead, the application's single page unloads and the previous page in the browser's history is presented.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] The traditional solution for SPAs has been to change the browser URL's hash fragment identifier in accord with the current screen state.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] This can be achieved with JavaScript, and causes URL history events to be built up within the browser.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] As long as the SPA is capable of resurrecting the same screen state from information contained within the URL hash, the expected back-button behavior is retained.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] To further address this issue, the HTML specification has introduced pushState and replaceState providing programmatic access to the actual URL and browser history.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Analytics tools such as Google Analytics rely heavily upon entire new pages loading in the browser, initiated by a new page load.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] After the first page load, all subsequent page and content changes are handled internally by the application, which should simply call a function to update the analytics package.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Failing to call such a function, the browser never triggers a new page load, nothing gets added to the browser history, and the analytics package has no idea who is doing what on the site.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Similarly to the problems encountered with search engine crawlers, DAST tools may struggle with these JavaScript-rich applications.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Problems can include the lack of hypertext links, memory usage concerns and resources loaded by the SPA typically being made available by an Application Programming Interface or API.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Single-page applications are still subject to the same security risks as traditional web pages such as Cross-Site Scripting (XSS), but also a host of other unique vulnerabilities such as data exposure via API and client-side logic and client-side enforcement of server-side security.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] In order to effectively scan a single-page application, a DAST scanner must be able to navigate the client-side application in a reliable and repeatable manner to allow discovery of all areas of the application and interception of all requests that the application sends to remote servers (e.g.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] It is possible to add page load events to a SPA using the HTML History API; this will help integrate analytics.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] The difficulty comes in managing this and ensuring that everything is being tracked accurately – this involves checking for missing reports and double entries.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Some frameworks provide free analytics integrations addressing most of the major analytics providers.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Developers can integrate them into the application and make sure that everything is working correctly, but there is no need to do everything from scratch.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] There are some ways of speeding up the initial load of a SPA, such as selective prerendering of the SPA landing/index page, caching and various code splitting techniques including lazy-loading modules when needed.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] But it's not possible to get away from the fact that it needs to download the framework, at least some of the application code; and will hit an API for data if the page is dynamic.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] This is a "pay me now, or pay me later" trade-off scenario.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] The question of performance and wait-times remains a decision that the developer must make.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] A SPA is fully loaded in the initial page load and then page regions are replaced or updated with new page fragments loaded from the server on demand.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] To avoid excessive downloading of unused features, a SPA will often progressively download more features as they become required, either small fragments of the page, or complete screen modules.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] In this way an analogy exists between "states" in a SPA and "pages" in a traditional website.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] Because "state navigation" in the same page is analogous to page navigation, in theory, any page-based web site could be converted to single-page replacing in the same page only the changed parts.
[src:quasar-framework/single-page-application] The SPA approach on the web is similar to the single-document interface (SDI) presentation technique popular in native desktop applications.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] Vue.js features an incrementally adaptable architecture that focuses on declarative rendering and component composition.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] The core library is focused on the view layer only.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] Advanced features required for complex applications such as routing, state management and build tooling are offered via officially maintained supporting libraries and packages.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] Vue.js allows for extending HTML with HTML attributes called directives.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] The directives offer functionality to HTML applications, and come as either built-in or user defined directives.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] Vue was created by Evan You after working for Google using AngularJS in several projects.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] He later summed up his thought process: "I figured, what if I could just extract the part that I really liked about Angular and build something really lightweight." The first source code commit to the project was dated July 2013, at which time it was originally named "Seed".
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] Vue was first publicly announced the following February, in 2014.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] Version names are often derived from manga and anime series, with the first letters arranged in alphabetical order.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] When a new major is released i.e. v3.y.z, the last minor i.e.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] 2.x.y will become a LTS release for 18 months (bug fixes and security patches) and for the following 18 months will be in maintenance mode (security patches only).
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] Vue 3 was officially released in September 2020.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] According to the *State of Vue.js Report 2025*, 96% of surveyed developers reported having used Vue 3.x.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] However, 35% also indicated that they used Vue 2.7.x in the past year, reflecting continued reliance on Vue 2 despite its end of support.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] The report also noted that more than a quarter of respondents encountered challenges when migrating from Vue 2 to Vue 3.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] According to the *State of Vue.js Report 2025*, the Vue's core team recommendation is reflected in developer adoption–over 80% of surveyed developers reported using Pinia while Vuex still had 38.4% usage, indicating ongoing reliance on the older library.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] Vue components extend basic HTML elements to encapsulate reusable code.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] At a high level, components are custom elements to which the Vue's compiler attaches behavior.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] In Vue, a component is essentially a Vue instance with pre-defined options.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] The code snippet below contains an example of a Vue component.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] Vue uses an HTML-based template syntax that allows binding the rendered DOM to the underlying Vue instance's data.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] All Vue templates are valid HTML that can be parsed by specification-compliant browsers and HTML parsers.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] Vue compiles the templates into virtual DOM render functions.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] A virtual Document Object Model (or "DOM") allows Vue to render components in its memory before updating the browser.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] Combined with the reactivity system, Vue can calculate the minimal number of components to re-render and apply the minimal amount of DOM manipulations when the app state changes.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] Vue users can use template syntax or choose to directly write render functions using hyperscript either through function calls or JSX.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] Render functions allow applications to be built from software components.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] Vue features a reactivity system that uses plain JavaScript objects and optimized re-rendering.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] Each component keeps track of its reactive dependencies during its render, so the system knows precisely when to re-render, and which components to re-render.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] Vue provides a variety of ways to apply transition effects when items are inserted, updated, or removed from the DOM.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] If the transition component provided JavaScript hooks, these hooks will be called at appropriate timings.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] If no CSS transitions/animations are detected and no JavaScript hooks are provided, the DOM operations for insertion and/or removal will be executed immediately on next frame.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] A traditional disadvantage of single-page applications (SPAs) is the inability to share links to the exact "sub" page within a specific web page.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] Because SPAs serve their users only one URL-based response from the server (it typically serves index.html or index.vue), bookmarking certain screens or sharing links to specific sections is normally difficult if not impossible.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] To solve this problem, many client-side routers delimit their dynamic URLs with a "hashbang" (#!), e.g.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] However, with HTML5 most modern browsers support routing without hashbangs.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] Vue provides an interface to change what is displayed on the page based on the current URL path – regardless of how it was changed (whether by emailed link, refresh, or in-page links).
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] Additionally, using a front-end router allows for the intentional transition of the browser path when certain browser events (i.e. clicks) occur on buttons or links.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] Vue itself doesn't come with front-end hashed routing.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] But the open-source "vue-router" package provides an API to update the application's URL, supports the back button (navigating history), and email password resets or email verification links with authentication URL parameters.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] It supports mapping nested routes to nested components and offers fine-grained transition control.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] With Vue, developers are already composing applications with small building blocks building larger components.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] With vue-router added to the mix, components must merely be mapped to the routes they belong to, and parent/root routes must indicate where children should render.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] Allows the User component to pass in the particular id of the user which was typed into the URL using the $route object's params key: `$route.params.id`.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] This template (varying by the params passed into the router) will be rendered into `<router-view></router-view>` inside the DOM's div#app.
[src:quasar-framework/vue-js] Although the Vue.js Ecosystem is generally very well-developed, developers point to some ecosystem gaps as one of the most important thing missing (as of March 2025 Developer Survey in *the State of Vue.js Report 2025*).
